	<tr>
	
		<td class="msg_user_cell" width="150" valign=top>
		
			 









<a href='/eq/view_profile?user.id=140101'  class="auth_text"  style="font-weight:bold;" >	
<span style='color:#336600;'>MelindhraZek</span></a>
			<br>
			
			<span style="font-size: 8pt;">
			Journeyman<br>
			
				Posts: 71<br>
				
				Registered: 05-10-2006
				
			</span>
			


			
			<br>
			
				<img src="/i/p.gif" height=8 width=150 border=0 alt=""><br>
				
			<a href='/eq/view_profile?user.id=140101'>







</a><br>
			


			
			<p>
			






<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=PVP&message.id=12454#M12454">3</a> of 8
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 450 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<DIV></DIV>
<P>OK, I'll don my flame retardant robe and play devil's advocate here.&nbsp; There shouldn't be a PvP progression, for the very reason that Raghnell stated.&nbsp; There isn't enough interest in Everquest PvP.&nbsp; The masses of people who like to PvP play other games, and for good reason; pvp in those other games is simply better designed and implemented in them than it is in EQ.&nbsp; Unless SOE was willing to spend serious time, thought capital, and effort into making a PvP system that was fun and sustainable, they're only going to repeat the failure of the Zeks, and they know it.&nbsp; Here are a few of the things that, IMHO, they'd have to do:</P>
<P>1) <STRONG>Eliminate Twinking</STRONG>.&nbsp; This would probably require putting much tighter level restrictions on lower level gear, and making more higher level gear no trade.&nbsp; Until you do this, you'll quickly be back in the same shape as you are on Zek, where it's very unattractive for someone to try to roll a trully new character unless they are willing to buy plat or have a high-level character already that can get them twink gear.</P>
<P>2) <STRONG>Make PvP A Legitimate&nbsp;Alternate Path for Character Advancement.&nbsp; </STRONG>The heart and soul of EQ is character advancement, but you cannot advance your character by pvping in everquest the way that it is implemented now.&nbsp; You can't gain XP, and you can't get better gear.&nbsp; Because of that, pve &gt; pvp in the long run in EQ.&nbsp; The individuals and guilds who are better at PVE will slowly but surely gain an insurmountable gear advantage over those who like to PvP, and so will get the upper hand in PvP not by PvP skill, but simply because they are far better geared.&nbsp; The hard-core game junkies who play 6 hours a day will eventually have an insurmountable upper-hand over those who play 6 hours a week as well, regardless of actual skill.</P>
<P>If it was possible to gain XP and loot via PvP then it would be a legitimate&nbsp;and sustainable alternative play-style.&nbsp; If you liked&nbsp;to PvE and raid, that's what you'd do.&nbsp; If you couldn't stand still for that and preferred to hone your PvP skills, you could get the same XP and gear by kicking someone's a** and taking it from them.&nbsp; The XP and gear that you get&nbsp;ought to scale to the level of the player that you killed.&nbsp; Kill someone two levels higher, and you might get an upgrade for your BP and a good bit of XP.&nbsp; Kill someone lower and you get zippity-do-dah.&nbsp; Enable item looting, but only for things that would be an upgrade for the looter.&nbsp; This&nbsp;provides a strong incentive to PvP with your equals or better, but a disincentive to&nbsp;PK&nbsp;lowbies and strip them&nbsp;just because you can.&nbsp;Right now, you can't advance yourself PvP.&nbsp; All you can do is grief the other guy and keep him from advancing.&nbsp; That needs to be reversed for PvP in EQ to be sustainable and fun.</P>
<P>3) <STRONG>Stop Trying to Make EQ PvP a Solo Game.&nbsp; </STRONG>The cumulative effect of nerfs on the game is a disaster, IMO, and most of them are intended to make it so that every single class can solo PvP.&nbsp; This is out of character with the rest of the game, and just as harmful as the introduction of potions and other gimmicks that allow classes that don't solo well to solo.&nbsp; So what if there are some classes that can solo PvP better than other classes?&nbsp; Nobody seems to care that a necro can solo PvE far better than a Warrior can.&nbsp; If you want to solo, you just don't roll a Warrior.&nbsp; It should be the same in PvP.&nbsp; If you want to be a lone ranger (no pun intended) there should be some classes that it makes sense to be, and others not so much.&nbsp; If you play a&nbsp;class that is more group dependant, you travel with a group, and PvP with a group.&nbsp; If SOE were to reimplement PVP for EQ (and I know they probalby won't) one of the commitments that they should make is to put the nerf bat away forever.&nbsp; Let the players adjust (by grouping up) to any inequalities that exist in the ability of one class or another to solo PvP.</P>
<P>Without some careful thought and attention to how PvP works in EQ, a PvP progression server would just be another loser sooner rather than later.&nbsp; It would be fun for a little while until the imbalances started to appear again, then people would drift away.&nbsp; EQ is a game that is late in it's lifecycle, and so, SOE is probably unwilling to risk a lot of capital to improve it.&nbsp; They're going to focus on the things that will continue to keep it in the black for as long as possible with as little new investment as possible.&nbsp; That means new expansions that people have to buy and new servers that appeal to the vast majority of the people who still play (blue players).&nbsp; As much as we who play on Zek might not like it, it's probably the right business decision.&nbsp; </P>	
		</td></tr>
		<tr>
		
		<td class="msg_date_cell" valign=bottom nowrap>
		<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
		 <span class=date_text>07-07-2006</span> <span class=time_text>10:14 AM</span>
		</span>
		</td>

		
			<td colspan=2 class="msg_rating_cell" valign=bottom nowrap 
			
