			<p>
			






<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=PVP&message.id=12490#M12490">8</a> of 8
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 15 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<div></div>I have returned to EQ after being absent for a few years, mainly because i started playing in the Ykesha era and the progression servers were a good chance for me to play the game without starting with 1k plat and friends powerlevelling me. All in all, I've had a lot of fun. More fun than I've had with any of the other MMOs I've played in the interim.<br><br>When I first started, I came from FPS like Unreal Tournament, so after getting my Necro into his high 40s on Xegony, i wanted to try my hand at the PvP that the game had to offer. I was sorely dissapointed. I spent at least 15 hours of /played time getting to level 7, because everytime i made camp and started farming mobs, trying to get my newbie quest gear, some twinked level 15 would come and stomp me, zone, and come back in 10 minutes. I believe the most offending character's was named Aholious, which makes it fairly certain, in my opinion, that it was a toon specifically made to do just that. Twink a warrior up with a bunch of gear that made him invinceable to any nub he could find that was trying to start out, and grief them incessantly. Keep in mind I love player-competitive games, and its not the griefing that even bothers me. It is the fact that there was absolutely no competition of skill in the engagement. A level 7 wizzy cant even hold a candle to a 15 warrior, regardless of the twinkage factor.<br><br>Mel raises a few good points on the topic. Everquest is a PvE game. MOBs drop loot and XP, therefore killing players will only cause them grief, not advance your character.<br>The PvE player will seize the advantage over time, and regardless of PvP skill, will have the upper hand. EQ was never meant to be a PvP game. It is the player cooperation and strategy that makes the game a lasting success. People who want to PvP play games like WoW or DAoC. I would make a toon on a PvP progression server in a heartbeat, but as soon as i got locked out of advancement by the timesinkers, I would go back to The Sleeper so I could enjoy progressing my character. Im sure a lot of the people who are screaming for a PvP Progression now would end up doing the same thing.<br><br>Commercially, I would have to say, a server with a 6 month population lifecycle would be disastrous for EQ as a whole. Sony is a business, and allocates a budget to EQ. Which Im sure is'nt as big as it used to be, seeing as though they are trying to get a new flagship game on the shelves. So if you enjoy playing EQ, be happy that its still even supported. Keep in mind that if EQ mades a bad business decision and goes into the red, Sony will drop it and move on and not give it a second thought.<br><br>I for one find that EQ has an unparalled community, in terms of maturity, fraternization and cooperation between players. Sure there's the "Leets" and the "Griefers", but overall the community is pretty stable. Thats why I came back. So I am in favor of EQ making&nbsp; the business decisions that it must to remain a viable product in the marketplace.<br><br><br>	
		</td></tr>
